1 dataset description

original = read.csv("Review.csv")
idx = sample(nrow(original),0.2*nrow(original))
review = original[idx,]

1.1 head of dataset

head(review)

1.2 dimension of dataset

dim(review)
## [1] 2000    2



2 text preparation

2.1 transform dataset into corpus

corpus = corpus(review, text_field = "review")
docvars(corpus,"id") = 1:ndoc(corpus)
summary(corpus)

2.2 create training and testing corpus

ind = sample(ndoc(corpus),0.7*ndoc(corpus),replace=F)

train = corpus_subset(corpus,id %in%ind) %>%
        tokens(remove_numbers = TRUE,
               remove_punct = TRUE,
               remove_symbols = TRUE,
               remove_twitter = TRUE,
               remove_url = TRUE,
               remove_hyphens = TRUE,
               include_docvars = TRUE) %>%
        dfm(tolower = TRUE,
            stem = TRUE,
            remove = stopwords("english"))
  
  
test = corpus_subset(corpus,!(id %in%ind)) %>%
        tokens(remove_numbers = TRUE,
               remove_punct = TRUE,
               remove_symbols = TRUE,
               remove_twitter = TRUE,
               remove_url = TRUE,
               remove_hyphens = TRUE,
               include_docvars = TRUE) %>%
        dfm(tolower = TRUE,
            stem = TRUE,
            remove = stopwords("english"))
train
## Document-feature matrix of: 1,400 documents, 14,918 features (99.4% sparse) and 2 docvars.

3 naive bayes model

3.1 build model

sentmod.nb = textmodel_nb(train,
                          docvars(train,"sentiment"),
                          distribution = "Bernoulli")

3.2 token probability of naive bayes

token.nb.prob = coef(sentmod.nb)
head(token.nb.prob)
##               Negative    Positive
## last       0.095367847 0.111940299
## weekend    0.006811989 0.004477612
## bought     0.028610354 0.011940299
## this'zombi 0.002724796 0.001492537
## movi       0.668937330 0.605970149
## bargain    0.008174387 0.005970149

3.3 predicted value/class of naive bayes

# only match feature appears in train corpus
dfmat_matched <- dfm_match(test, features=featnames(train))

# actual 'sentiment' class
actual_class <- docvars(dfmat_matched, "sentiment")

# predicted 'sentiment' probability
predicted_value.nb <- predict(sentmod.nb, 
                              newdata=dfmat_matched, 
                              type="probability")

# predicted 'sentiment' class
predicted_class.nb <- predict(sentmod.nb, 
                              newdata=dfmat_matched)

tab_class <- table(actual_class,predicted_class.nb)
tab_class
##             predicted_class.nb
## actual_class Negative Positive
##     Negative      282       20
##     Positive      119      179

4 ridge regression model

library(glmnet)
library(foreach)
library(iterators)
library(parallel)
library(doParallel)

parallel computing to speed up

cl = makeCluster(4)
registerDoParallel(cl)

4.1 build ridge regression model

sentmod.ridge <- cv.glmnet(x=train,
                           y=docvars(train)$sentiment,
                           family="binomial", 
                           alpha=0,
                           nfolds=5,
                           parallel=TRUE, 
                           intercept=TRUE,
                           type.measure="class")

4.2 predicted value/class of ridge

predicted_value.ridge <- predict(sentmod.ridge,
                                 newx=dfmat_matched,
                                 s="lambda.min")[,1]

predicted_class.ridge <- rep(NA,length(predicted_value.ridge))

predicted_class.ridge[predicted_value.ridge>0] <- "Positive"
predicted_class.ridge[predicted_value.ridge<0] <- "Negative"
tab_class.ridge <- table(actual_class,predicted_class.ridge)
tab_class.ridge
##             predicted_class.ridge

##     Positive       72      226

5 lasso regression model

sentmod.lasso <- cv.glmnet(x=train,
                           y=docvars(train)$sentiment,
                           family="binomial", 
                           alpha=1,
                           nfolds=5,
                           parallel=TRUE, 
                           intercept=TRUE,
                           type.measure="class")

5.1 predicted value/class of lasso

predicted_value.lasso <- predict(sentmod.lasso, newx=dfmat_matched,s="lambda.min")[,1]
predicted_class.lasso <- rep(NA,length(predicted_value.lasso))
predicted_class.lasso[predicted_value.lasso>0] <- "Positive"
predicted_class.lasso[predicted_value.lasso<0] <- "Negative"
tab_class.lasso <- table(actual_class,predicted_class.lasso)

6 evaluation

data.frame(model = c("naive bayes","ridge","lasso"),
           accuracy = c("74.5%","76.17%","78.33%"))

Lasso model has the largest accuracy.

Moreover, Lasso model shrinks coefficients of the majority of features to zero, and only 131 out of 15101 features have none-zero coefficients.



7 save output of 3 models

7.1 Naive bayes token probability

token.nb.prob = data.frame(row=rownames(token.nb.prob),
                           token.nb.prob,
                           row.names = 1:nrow(token.nb.prob))
head(token.nb.prob)

7.2 joined probability and coefficients

coef = left_join(coef.ridge,coef.lasso,by="row")
probability = left_join(coef,token.nb.prob,by="row") %>%
              select(-c(column.x,column.y)) 
            
colnames(probability) = c("feature", 
                          "ridge.coef",
                          "lasso.coef",
                          "nb.neg.prob",
                          "nb.pos.prob")
probability
